                         <div id=3D"note-1-anchor" class=3D"widget little_g=
ems little-gems-module-anchor-1 content-section-with-header">
    <div class=3D"content-section-header">
        <div class=3D"d-flex align-items-center">
            <img class=3D"pe-2" src=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dist=
-cross-dungarees/2025-12-09--19-02-49-ise9p/images/svg/redesign/lightbulb-i=
con.svg" role=3D"presentation" alt=3D"">
            <h2>Did you know?</h2>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"content-section-body">
                <p>Solving calculus equations on a chalkboard allows one to=
 erase mistakes, and also hints at the word=E2=80=99s rocky, and possibly c=
halky, past. <em>Calculus</em> entered English in the 17th century from Lat=
in, in which it referred to a pebble, often one used specifically for addin=
g and subtracting on a counting board. The word thus became associated with=
 computation; the phrase <em>ponere calculos</em>, literally, =E2=80=9Cto p=
lace pebbles,=E2=80=9D meant =E2=80=9Cto carry out a computation.=E2=80=9D =
The Latin <em>calculus</em>, in turn, is thought to perhaps come from the n=
oun <em>calx</em>, meaning =E2=80=9Clime=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Climestone,=E2=
=80=9D which is also the ancestor of the English word <em>chalk</em>. Today=
, in addition to referring to an advanced branch of mathematics, <em>calcul=
us</em> can also be used generally for the act of solving or figuring somet=
hing out, and as a medical term for the <a href=3D"https://www.merriam-webs=
ter.com/dictionary/tartar">tartar</a> that forms on teeth, among other thin=
gs. Whichever way it=E2=80=99s used, we think that <em>calculus</em> rocks.=
</p>
    </div>
</div>
