  <p class=3D"et">
                borrowed from Latin, "pebble, bladder or kidney stone, pebb=
le used for calculating on a counting board, method or result of calculatio=
n, account," perhaps irregular diminutive of <em class=3D"mw_t_it">calc-, c=
alx</em> "lime, limestone"  =E2=80=94 more at <a href=3D"https://www.merria=
m-webster.com/dictionary/chalk#h1" class=3D"mw_t_mat">chalk <span class=3D"=
text-lowercase">entry</span> 1</a>            </p>
                                    <p class=3D"et_snote ps-0">
               =20
<span class=3D"note-txt text-uppercase">Note:</span>
    This etymology was accepted by the Latin grammarian Sextus Pompeius Fes=
tus, though the senses differ markedly. Perhaps more likely is a connection=
 with Greek <em class=3D"mw_t_it">k=C3=A1chl=C4=93x</em> "shingle (on a sho=
reline)," usually associated with <em class=3D"mw_t_it">kachl=C3=A1zein</em=
> "to splash, murmur, crash (of waves)," taken to be onomatopoeic. However,=
 R. Beekes (<em class=3D"mw_t_it">Etymological Dictionary of Greek</em>) al=
ludes to the forms <em class=3D"mw_t_it">k=C3=B3chlax</em> (in the Septuagi=
nt) and <em class=3D"mw_t_it">=C3=A1chlax</em> (in the <em class=3D"mw_t_it=
">Suda,</em> a tenth-century Byzantine encyclopedia), variants with feature=
s (<em class=3D"mw_t_it">o</em> alternating with <em class=3D"mw_t_it">a, k=
</em> alternating with zero) that, according to Beekes, mark borrowing from=
 a non-Indo-European substratum. This might presuppose that both <em class=
=3D"mw_t_it">calculus</em> and <em class=3D"mw_t_it">k=C3=A1chl=C4=93x</em>=
 were borrowed from a common source.            </p>
